title: For Sale/Trade:  KS-47 Rifle, 7.62x39 AR Platform, New and Unfired
location: Raeford, Fort Bragg, Fayetteville, Fayetteville, North Carolina
postcontent: I've got a new, unfired PSA KS-47 rifle for sale. These KS-47s are an AR platform that is chambered in 7.62x39, and accepts any AK magazine. Way cheaper to shoot than firing 5.56 or 223, plus much more punch! If you're unfamiliar with these rifles, check out the video on youtube (PSA KS47 -vs- CMMG Mutant).The PSA KS47 is based on the AR15, and combines the modular construction, accuracy and precision of the AR platform with the stopping power and the magazine options of the AK. While the current AR47 fires the 7.62x39 AK round, it uses modified AR-style magazines that are not nearly as plentiful as AK-style magazines, that were optimized for reliable feeding of the 7.62x39 round. The KS47 lets the AK shooter capitalize on his inventory of magazines and ammo with an AR-style platform. Unlike the AK, where the barrel is permanently pressed into the receiver, the KS47 features an AR-style modular configuration which consists of a barreled upper receiver, and a lower receiver that houses the fire control group and magazine. I'm asking $900 for the rifle with one steel or PMAG 30 round magazine (buyers choice). Would trade for a Sig Sauer P226 MK25.Can add additional items for the right trade.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Unfired 1951 Commercial Colt Government Model 1911
postcontent: This commercial 1911 was part of a batch found in a warehouse by a distributor in the late 2000s, and sold to buyers sight unseen -- that is, I didn't get to choose which gun in the batch I received. For me, the blind order 1911 was going to serve as a starting platform for a bullseye competition gun. However, when I took possession of it I was blown away to find the gun had dried cosmoline inside, and no carbon or copper on the breech face or barrel: ostensibly, in unfired condition. I chose to keep it that way, and the gun has never been fired by me, and only handled for periodic cleaning.Research on www.sitem1911.com puts this Colt's year of manufacturer at 1951. The bluing appears original: deep, reflective, and reminiscent of an Art Deco age where attention to detail was paramount. It shows handling wear, primarily at the muzzle end on the dust cover; there are fine lines in the bluing here and there, and an "idiot mark" from an uncareful reassembly somewhere along the line. While not 100%, this classic has carried its 66 years very gracefully.The period-correct box arrived in my possession too tattered to salvage, and I no longer have it.Comes with original Colt 7 round magazine, in similar condition to pistol.Higher-definition photos on request: seven Owe Won, three 0 sicks, for 3 ate 3.FtF with proof of MO residency is fine.
